  "module1": {
    "clean_text": "A [AGE] male patient presented with arthritis, eye pain, itching, and redness. He had a history of allergic rhinitis and was not on any medication prior to evaluation. Laboratory results showed serum urea at 102.1 mg/dL (12.84–42.8 mg/dL), creatinine at 4.66 mg/dL (0.70–1.20 mg/dL), eGFR at 13 mL/min/1.73 m2 (60–120 mL/min/1.73 m2), serum albumin at 30.4 gr/L (35–52 gr/L), blood eosinophil count at 1.23 103/μL (0.03–0.59 103/μL), and C-reactive protein at 69.8 mg/L (0–5 mg/L). Urine analysis showed 1+ proteinuria, with no hematuria or leukocyturia, and normal urine microscopy. A 24-hour urine collection revealed 1527.5 mg/day proteinuria. Additional laboratory findings included C3c at 0.38 g/L (0.9–1.8 g/L), C4 at < 0.02 g/L (0.1–0.4 g/L), serum amyloid A at 50.70 mg/dL (5.7–8.2 mg/dL), IgG at 37.83 g/L (7–16 g/L), α1 globulin at 6% (2.9–4.9), β1 globulin at 3.2% (4.7–7.2), β2 globulin at 7.8% (3.2–6.5), and γ globulin at 39.4% (11.1–18.8). Liver and thyroid function tests, as well as pancreatic enzymes, were normal. Blood and urine cultures showed no growth. Rheumatoid factor and autoantibody tests were negative. Contrast-enhanced abdominal computed tomography revealed an inflamed appearance in the adipose tissue in the left pararectal region, loss of corticomedullary separation, and hypodense patchy areas in both kidneys. The respiratory system examination was normal, there were no rashes, and antibodies (ANA, pANCA, cANCA, antiGBM, etc.) were negative. There was no clinical picture of rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis.",
    "phi_map": {
      "AGE": "52-year-old"
    },
    "patient_info": {
      "sex": "male"
    }
  },
